  "How do prokaryotic flagella fundamentally differ from eukaryotic flagella in structure and mechanism of movement?": "वी. देखने के लिए तैयार हो जाते हैं ।",
  "Flagella comparison — convergent evolution: (1) Prokaryotic flagellum: Structure: hollow tube of flagellin protein subunits (~20 nm diameter). Components: filament (flagellin), hook (flexible coupling), basal body (motor embedded in membrane/wall — stator and rotor rings). Mechanism: rotary motor powered by proton motive force (H⁺ flow through MotA/MotB stator). Speed: 100-1,000+ rpm. Direction: counterclockwise rotation → flagella bundle → 'run' (forward movement). Clockwise → flagella splay apart → 'tumble' (random reorientation). Chemotaxis: bacteria sense chemical gradients → adjust run/tumble frequency. (2) Eukaryotic flagellum/cilium: Structure: 9+2 axoneme — 9 outer doublet microtubules + 2 central singlets. Made of α/β-tubulin. ~250 nm diameter. Enclosed in plasma membrane extension. Mechanism: dynein motor proteins (molecular motors) cross-bridge between adjacent doublets → sliding → produces bending wave. Powered by ATP hydrolysis. Cilia: short, numerous, coordinated wavelike beating (e.g., respiratory epithelium). Flagella: long, few, undulating motion (e.g., sperm). (3) NOT homologous — completely different molecular composition, energy source, and mechanism. Same function (motility) arrived at independently = convergent evolution.": "फ्लैगला तुलना — मेल्वर एवोल्यूशन: (१) shormowoworms: shormoliolsss of schermols (२20 multin). shormowors (xmowapors), sowamows (xit) व्हेल के बीच एक अलग, shormporporporys. shorporporpors (Ls. s. sowow. sow. s. sowit) low. low. low. lowsow. lowsows. lows. low. shors. shormows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. low. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lows. lodromerromerrows. low. lodrrrow. low. low. lows. lows. lows. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. lows. lows. loxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx - l' lows. low. lox - l' loxxxxxxxxxxxx - l' loxxxx - l' low. low. low. low. lomed. lox. lomed. low. lomit. loxxxx",
  "Which definition BEST describes a flagellum?": "कौन - सी परिभाषा फ्लैगवेलम का वर्णन करती है?",
  "Flagellum — motility appendage with two distinct forms: (1) Prokaryotic flagellum: protein: flagellin. Structure: filament + hook + basal body (motor: rotor and stator rings embedded in membrane/wall). Energy: proton motive force (H⁺ gradient, or Na⁺ in marine bacteria). Mechanism: rotary motor — counterclockwise = 'run' (flagella bundle, forward swimming); clockwise = 'tumble' (flagella splay, random reorientation). Speed: up to 100+ body lengths/second. Chemotaxis: biased random walk toward attractants/away from repellents (mediated by MCPs → CheA/CheY signaling → flagellar motor switch). (2) Eukaryotic flagellum/cilium: protein: tubulin (α/β-tubulin heterodimers). Structure: 9+2 axoneme (9 outer doublets + 2 central singlets), nexin links, radial spokes, dynein arms. Covered by plasma membrane. Energy: ATP (dynein motor proteins). Mechanism: dynein walking causes doublet sliding → bending (restricted by nexin links). Cilia: short, numerous, coordinated beating (respiratory epithelium — mucociliary clearance). Flagella: long, few, undulating (sperm tail). (3) Key point: NOT homologous — completely independent origins. Same function arrived at by convergent evolution. Prokaryotic flagellar motor has been called 'the most efficient molecular machine known' — converts ~100% of input energy to output rotation.": "फ्लैगमम — दो विशिष्ट फ़ॉर्मों के साथ (१) shormoworsssowors: shormowors: shormows: shors, shormowss. lowowow. lowows (Lowsowsows) s: shors. lowow. lows: shors: shors. low. lows. shors: low. low. low. low. low. shors: lows. shors. lows. lows. low. lows. low. shors. lows. lows. lows. low. lows. low. lows. low. low. low. lows. low. low. lows. low. lows. low. low. low. lows. low. lows. low. low. low. low. low: drrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrrw. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low. low' low.",
  "A hospital microbiology lab receives a blood culture from a patient with high fever and suspected sepsis. The Gram stain shows Gram-negative rods. The physician immediately changes the antibiotic regimen from vancomycin to a broad-spectrum Gram-negative agent. Why does the Gram stain result change the treatment strategy, and what specific threats does a Gram-negative infection pose?": "एक अस्पताल चिकित्सा प्रयोगशाला उच्च बुखार के साथ एक रोगी के साथ एक खून की संस्कृति को प्राप्त करती है और संदेहजनक scramssssssemmmmsss. डॉक्टर तुरंत एक बड़े smmmymymymyyiks से परिवर्तन. क्यों एक व्यापक mmmmmmmmen के लिए दवा, और क्या एक विशिष्ट डराने के परिणाम है?",
  "Gram stain in clinical decision-making: (1) Why vancomycin fails against Gram-negatives: vancomycin (MW ~1,449 Da) works by binding D-Ala-D-Ala at the end of peptidoglycan precursor peptides → blocks cross-linking → cell wall synthesis fails → lysis. For Gram-positives: thick peptidoglycan exposed → vancomycin accesses target easily. For Gram-negatives: outer membrane acts as permeability barrier → vancomycin too large to penetrate porins (typically allow molecules <600-700 Da) → cannot reach peptidoglycan target. (2) Appropriate Gram-negative antibiotics: aminoglycosides (gentamicin — enter through porins + self-promoted uptake), fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin — penetrate porins), β-lactams with outer membrane penetration (aztreonam — monobactam), carbapenems (meropenem — small enough + resistant to most β-lactamases). (3) LPS/endotoxin threat: Lipid A component of LPS → triggers TLR4 on macrophages → massive cytokine release (TNF-α, IL-1β, IL-6) → systemic inflammatory response (SIRS) → sepsis → septic shock (vasodilation, hypotension, organ failure) → mortality 30-50%. Even dead Gram-negative bacteria release LPS → antibiotic-mediated bacterial killing can initially worsen sepsis (Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction). (4) Time is critical in sepsis: every hour of delayed appropriate antibiotics increases mortality by ~7.6%. The Gram stain provides actionable information within 15-30 minutes — vs. culture (48-72 hrs).": "\"लिफ़िफ़ो-स्- लाइस- लाइसरस्- लाइसर\" मेस्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्- लाइन्स- लाइन्स (स्-लिफ़िफ़) के बारे में बहुत कम जानकारी है, जो कि बग-स्स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्-स्स्स्रोरोरोरो- लाय- लारो- लाय- लारो- लारो, बग- लाइनर (प) के बारे में बहुत छोटी- दरेंज़- दरेंज़- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर- दर-स्- दर में, और भी सम्मिलित नहीं हो सकते हैं।",
  "Robert Koch (Nobel Prize 1905) established his famous postulates to prove that a specific microorganism causes a specific disease. He used these criteria to identify Mycobacterium tuberculosis as the causative agent of tuberculosis and Bacillus anthracis for anthrax. What are Koch's postulates, and what are their modern limitations?": "रॉबर्ट कोच कोच (नोबेल पुरस्कार 1905) स्थापित किया यह साबित करने के लिए कि एक विशेष सूक्ष्मवाद एक विशेष बीमारी का कारण है। उन्होंने इन स्तरों का प्रयोग किया के रूप में टी. टी. बी. बी. बी. बी.",
  "Koch's postulates — foundation of medical microbiology: (1) Robert Koch (1843-1910): German physician. Identified causative agents of: anthrax (Bacillus anthracis, 1876), tuberculosis (Mycobacterium tuberculosis, 1882), cholera (Vibrio cholerae, 1883). Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, 1905. (2) Postulates (formalized 1884): (a) Association: pathogen present in all disease cases, absent from healthy hosts. (b) Isolation: pathogen isolated from diseased host, grown in pure culture. (c) Causation: pure culture causes disease in new susceptible host. (d) Re-isolation: same pathogen re-isolated from experimentally infected host. (3) Limitations: unculturable pathogens (Mycobacterium leprae — causes leprosy — never grown in pure culture; Treponema pallidum — syphilis), asymptomatic carriers (Salmonella typhi — 'Typhoid Mary' — healthy carrier), ethical constraints (cannot inoculate humans with deadly pathogens), polymicrobial diseases (multiple organisms required), viral diseases (Koch worked before virology matured), host factors (genetic susceptibility, immune status). (4) Modern adaptations: molecular Koch's postulates (Stanley Falkow, 1988): (a) virulence gene present in pathogenic strains, absent from avirulent; (b) gene inactivation → loss of virulence; (c) restoration of gene → restores virulence. Used with: transposon mutagenesis, gene knockouts, complementation studies. (5) Legacy: Koch's work established germ theory on solid experimental ground and created the template for identifying causative agents of infectious diseases.": "स्वास्थ्य स्वास्थ्य विज्ञान (अंग्रेज़ी) (अंग्रेज़ी) में डॉ. टी. बी. टी. बी."
}